Caesarstone Sdot-Yam Ltd v Ceramiche Caesar SpA

Caesarstone Sdot-Yam Ltd v Ceramiche Caesar SpA
[2016] 2 SLR 1129; [2016] SGHC 45

Case Number:Tribunal Appeal No 12 of 2015
Decision Date:29 March 2016
Tribunal/Court:High Court
Coram: George Wei J
Counsel Name(s): Prithipal Singh and Chow Jian Hong (Mirandah Law LLP) for the appellant; Melvin Pang (Amica Law LLC) for the respondent.
Parties: CAESARSTONE SDOT-YAM LTD — CERAMICHE CAESAR SpA

Evidence – Proof of evidence – Judicial notice – Applicant tendered Accounting and Corporate Regulatory Authority report showing number of entities whose names contained common denominator “Caesar” – Whether judicial notice should be taken of such fact

Trade Marks and Trade Names – Registration criteria – Conflicts with earlier marks – Registration of trade mark opposed based on earlier trade mark – Whether trade mark similar – Whether likelihood of confusion arising – Whether trade mark well known – Sections 2(7), 2(8), 8(2)(b) and 8(4)(b)(i) Trade Marks Act (Cap 332, 2005 Rev Ed)

Facts

Caesarstone Sdot-Yam Ltd (“the Applicant”) applied to register the CAESARSTONE mark (“CAESARSTONE Mark”) in Classes 19, 20, 35 and 37 of the Trade Mark Register. Ceramiche Caesar SpA (“the Opponent”) opposed the registration of the CAESARSTONE Mark in Class 19 on the basis of its earlier CAESAR mark (“CAESAR Mark”). The Principal Assistant Registrar (“the PAR”) allowed the opposition on two grounds: (a) the marks were similar on the whole and there was a real likelihood of confusion on the part of the public; and (b) the CAESAR Mark was well known in Singapore at the date on which the CAESARSTONE Mark was applied for and there was a confusing connection that caused blurring. The Applicant appealed the PAR’s decision to allow the opposition.

Held, allowing the appeal:

(1)    To succeed under s 8(2)(b) of the Trade Marks Act (Cap 332, 2005 Rev Ed) (“the TMA”), the Opponent had to establish that: (a) the marks were similar; (b) the CAESARSTONE Mark was to be registered for goods and services that were similar or identical to those for which the CAESAR Mark was protected; and (c) there existed a likelihood of confusion arising from the two similarities. There was no dispute on the second requirement in this appeal: at [19] and [20].

(2)    Under the common law, the court could take judicial notice of: (a) facts which were so notorious or so clearly established that they were beyond the subject of reasonable dispute; and (b) facts which were capable of being immediately and accurately shown to exist by authoritative sources. Since ACRA records was an authoritative source of the names of business entities past and present, judicial notice could be taken of the ACRA report which showed how commonly “Caesar” was used as a corporate name: at [38] and [39].

(3)    In cases involving composite marks, the mark had to ultimately be assessed as a whole. Where all the other components were negligible, an assessment might be carried out solely on the basis of the dominant elements. It is, however, possible for a composite mark to not have any dominant feature. Further, where the composite mark consisted of a word and a device, there was no presumption that the word spoke louder: at [52] to [54].

(4)    The opposition under s 8(2)(b) of the TMA failed. The marks were visually dissimilar and there was little or no conceptual similarity. While there was some aural similarity, the marks when examined in their totality were dissimilar. Even if the marks were similar, there was no real likelihood of confusion. The nature of goods and the mode of purchase went towards reducing the likelihood of confusion, if there was any in the first place: at [80], [118], [120] and [122].

(5)    In assessing whether the opposition under s 8(4)(a) read with s 8(4)(b)(i) of the TMA was made out, the relevant sector of the public comprised consumers, retailers and distributors of, inter alia, tiles and flooring materials that fell within Class 19 as well as professionals such as interior designers and architects: at [150].

(6)    The opposition under s 8(4)(a) read with s 8(4)(b)(i) of the TMA failed because the Opponent had not discharged its burden of proving that the CAESAR Mark was well known to the relevant sector of the public. While the CAESAR Mark had been successfully enforced in other jurisdictions, the extent to which the CAESAR Mark was used in Singapore was unclear: at [153], [155], [156] and [158].

[Observation: There was some uncertainty as to whether the court was entitled to take into account developments in the reputation of the CAESARSTONE Mark between the application and the hearing. However, it was not necessary to make a conclusive determination on this point since there was no likelihood of confusion both at the date of the application or the date of the opposition hearing: at [104] and [105].]
